  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Level:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- International Money Laundering Abatement and Anti-Terrorism Financing Act\n\n2. State Level:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- These often mirror federal regulations and provide additional enforcement mechanisms\n\n3. Key Provisions:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate record-keeping\n- Establish criminal penalties for money laundering\n- Impose fines and potential imprisonment\n- Enable asset seizure\n\n4. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\nThese statutes are designed to prevent, detect, and prosecute financial crimes involving the concealment of illegally obtained money through a series of transactions intended to appear legitimate.\n\nEach law has specific provisions addressing different aspects of money laundering prevention and prosecution.",
